<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-482-905  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 482 905.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 8 1990 v7 n40 p53(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>KnowledgeSet adds Windows support to CD ROM package. (KnowledgeSetCorp. introduces new version of CD ROM full-text search andretrieval software for Windows 3.0 workstations) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Higgins, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>KnowledgeSet Corp introduces a Windows 3.0 version of its GraphicKnowledge Retrieval system (KRS) CD-ROM full-text search andretrieval software.andP;  The program, introduced at the 1990 CD ROMExpo in Boston, will let Windows 3.0 workstation users search forand retrieve information stored in CD ROM databases onNetBIOS-compatible local area networks.andP;  The new program letsusers access data from mixed text and graphics documents andprovides both full-text and hypertext searching capabilities.andO;Users can enter a single word or a more complex query to find alldocuments in a database meeting search criteria such as proximityand field-specific searching.andP;  Hypertext links let users connectreferences, footnotes, citations, bibliographies and supplementaldata to any type of related information.andP;  Graphic KRS for Windows3.0 will sell for $300 per workstation.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   KnowledgeSet Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Graphic Knowledge Retrieval System (Search software) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionCD-ROMSearchingInformation Storage and Retrieval.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Steve HigginsandM;KnowledgeSet Corp. announced a new version of its CD ROM full-text search andretrieval software last week that brings Windows 3.0 workstation users intothe fold.andM;Unveiled at CD ROM Expo '90 in Boston, the new Graphic Knowledge RetrievalSystem (KRS) version will give Windows 3.0 users on NetBIOS-compatible LANsthe ability to search for and retrieve information stored in CD ROMdatabases, said Gail Bower, KnowledgeSet's product marketing manager.andM;The Windows version, due in the first quarter of next year, lets users accessinformation from mixed text and graphics documents such as reference manuals,technical documentation and illustrated parts catalogs.andP;  Users cansimultaneously display various pieces of information -- such as a document'stable of contents, graphics, annotation and pages of the document itself --in different on-screen windows, Bower said.andM;Currently available for Macintosh, Unix and GEM environments, Graphic KRSprovides both full-text and hypertext search capabilities.andM;The full-text search function allows users to enter a single word or a morecomplex query to find all documents in the database that meet the searchcriteria.andP;  Search methods include proximity -- for example, &quot;all referencesto Joe Smith that are near IBM&quot; -- and field-specific searching.andP;  When asearch is concluded, the program displays a title list along with the numberof matches found.andM;The program's hypertext links let users connect any type of relatedinformation from within the document text, including references, citations,footnotes, bibliographies and supplemental data and graphics.andM;&quot;The release of a Windows version makes it advantageous for many DOS users toadopt KRS,&quot; said Steve Soto, director of technology research at HelgersonAssociates Inc., a research firm in Falls Church, Va., that specializes in CDROM.andP;  &quot;Now they can run it as another Windows application without having toadd a whole new operating environment to use it.&quot;andM;Users of the new version will also be able to take advantage of KnowlegeSet'sapplication programming interface to develop custom applications andinterfaces.andM;The Windows 3.0 version of Graphic KRS will cost $300 per workstation.andM;KnowledgeSet Corp., of Mountain View, Calif., can be reached at (800)456-0469.andO;</TEXT></DOC>